# Adaptive Algorithmic Source License — Volume II
## R8 Non-Newtonian Liquidity Edition (AASL-R8 v2.0)

> Inherited intellectually from https://opensource.org/license/APL-1.0

## PREAMBLE

This license extends the framework of AASL v1.0 to a class of protocols whose value derives not from a particular implementation but from the geometric, spectral and information-theoretic structure of their state evolution. The R8 protocol family — beginning with its decentralized exchange (DEX) instantiation and extending across the full surface of automated finance — implements **Non-Newtonian Liquidity**: a class of automated market mechanisms that resist large informational shocks and flow around small ones, exhibiting a defensive nonlinearity that emerges from the geometry of the simplex rather than from any specific bonding curve.

Because the value of such protocols is carried by their **mathematical signature** — not by lines of code — this license protects the **Protocol Logic** at the level on which it is in fact creative: the manifold, the metric, the invariant, the spectrum.

Where AASL v1.0 established the principle of priority of logic over code, this Volume II provides the **operational machinery** required to enforce it: a multi-criterion identity test resistant to obfuscation, a binding across runtimes, and a mechanism of automated on-chain arbitration between the Licensor (DAO) and any party engaged in the extraction of value from the Protocol Logic.

---

## 1. DEFINITIONS

1.1. **Protocol Logic** — the totality of mathematical structures, geometric invariants, spectral decompositions, oracle-driven calibration schemes, automated arbitration rules and informational topologies that define the unique state evolution of the System.

1.2. **R8 Family** — the family of protocols implementing Non-Newtonian Liquidity through invariants in centered log-ratio (CLR / Aitchison) geometry with a direct positive-definite risk operator and a complex-valued covariance structure carrying causal (Lévy-area) information. The Family includes, without limitation:

   (a) **DeFi venues** — spot decentralized exchanges (DEX), perpetual and dated derivatives, lending and credit protocols, structured products, intent-based execution venues;

   (b) **InfoFi venues** — opinion markets, attention markets, creator-coin protocols, prediction markets, and any further venue in which the underlying tradable quantity is informational rather than financial in the classical sense;

   (c) **RWA traceability layers** and any further protocol whose state evolution falls within the mathematical envelope defined in §3.

   Categories (a) and (b) are recognized as the two principal applications of Non-Newtonian Liquidity.

1.3. **Implementation** — any expression of the Protocol Logic in source code, byte code, electronic circuitry, neural-network weights, ZK-circuit constraints, hardware description, agentic prompt graphs, or any further executable form, irrespective of language, virtual machine, layer, runtime or substrate.

1.4. **Licensor** — the R8 DAO (or the legal entity acting as its trustee at the relevant time), holding rights to the Protocol Logic on behalf of the community of contributors.

1.5. **Change Date** — the date specified at protocol genesis (or as subsequently amended by DAO vote) after which all commercial restrictions of this license expire and the Protocol Logic transitions to GPL-3.0-or-later.

1.6. **Technological Context** — the state of the art at the time of any dispute, including the available means of automation, decentralization, computation, formal verification and program synthesis. The Technological Context is the reference frame against which questions of identity, equivalence and reproducibility are decided.

1.7. **Mathematical Signature** — the tuple consisting of (a) the topology and metric of the state space; (b) the invariant function and its level sets; (c) the spectrum of the Hessian of the invariant in the operative coordinate system; (d) the signature of the covariance operator in the metric-tensor sense; (e) the anti-symmetric / imaginary part of any path-dependent kernel; (f) the family of automorphisms preserving the invariant. Two systems share a Mathematical Signature when these objects coincide up to a smooth change of chart.

1.8. **Obfuscation** — any transformation of an Implementation whose intent or foreseeable effect is to conceal the equivalence of its Mathematical Signature to that of the Protocol Logic, including (without limitation) renaming, restructuring, polynomial reparameterization, basis change, stochastic dithering of constants, transpilation across virtual machines, agentic re-derivation through large language models, or distribution of the logic across multiple subsystems each of which is individually below the equivalence threshold.

1.9. **Volvo Transfer** — the obligation, derived from the Volvo Principle (after Nils Bohlin / Volvo, 1959), of a participant whose two technologies are mature enough to autonomously sustain a third to transfer one of the two — with all intellectual property — to the Licensor, who shall release it to the public domain.

1.10. **Maximalist Deployment Environment** — a substrate in which the blockchain or distributed ledger is structurally isolated from the external world and communicates with it solely through cryptoeconomic oracles, and in which finality, consensus and state validity rest on cryptoeconomic incentives without explicit reputational guarantees of identifiable participants. By way of non-exhaustive illustration, the following are recognized as Maximalist Deployment Environments: **Ethereum, Bitcoin, Solana, Monad**, and any further Layer-1 or Layer-2 system meeting the foregoing structural criteria.

1.11. **Hybrid Reputational Environment** — a substrate in which decentralized technologies are intentionally interleaved with the operational layer of traditional finance and admit substantial intervention by authoritative participants who stake their reputation on the integrity of the system. By way of non-exhaustive illustration, the following are recognized as Hybrid Reputational Environments: **Cardano, the Internet Computer Protocol (ICP), and Guardtime KSI**, and any further substrate meeting the foregoing structural criteria.

---

## 2. GRANT AND LIMITATIONS

2.1. **Permitted Uses.** The Licensor grants any Licensee a non-exclusive, royalty-free right to study, modify, reason about, formally verify, fork for research, and deploy in non-commercial settings any Implementation of the Protocol Logic.

2.2. **Restricted Uses.** Until the Change Date, the following are prohibited without written authorization of the Licensor (executed by DAO vote): (a) any deployment that extracts protocol fees, spread, MEV, rebates, or any other economic surplus from third parties; (b) any creation of a competing platform, fork, interface, aggregator, frontend, indexer or routing layer whose operation depends on the Protocol Logic; (c) any tokenization, securitization, or financial wrapping of positions or claims arising from the Protocol Logic.

2.3. **Independence of Form.** The restriction in §2.2 attaches to the Protocol Logic and not to any specific Implementation. It applies regardless of language, runtime, layer, chain, virtual machine, hardware substrate, or whether the Implementation was produced by human authorship, clean-room reconstruction, transpilation, or AI-assisted re-derivation.

2.4. **Multi-Protocol Scope.** Because the R8 Family is a family — and because Non-Newtonian Liquidity provides a working substrate for many protocols — the restrictions of §2.2 apply uniformly across all members of the Family. A Licensee permitted to operate one member of the Family acquires no implicit right with respect to any other member.

2.5. **Sphere of Application: Maximalist Scope and Hybrid Reputational Carve-Out.**

   2.5.1. **Maximalist Scope.** The restrictions of §2.2 apply **exclusively** to Implementations deployed in a Maximalist Deployment Environment as defined in §1.10. The protective function of this license is calibrated to environments in which the integrity of state evolution rests on cryptoeconomic incentives alone, and in which the Mathematical Signature is the only meaningful guarantor against value extraction.

   2.5.2. **Hybrid Reputational Carve-Out.** Nothing in this license restricts the development, deployment or commercialization of products and protocols in a Hybrid Reputational Environment as defined in §1.11. The Licensor expressly disclaims any restriction over Implementations operating in such environments, recognizing that in the presence of identifiable reputational guarantors the protective function carried by the Mathematical Signature is partly substituted by traditional contract law, regulatory oversight, and reputational risk borne by the authoritative participants. This carve-out is structural, not provisional: it reflects the Licensor's view that the two worlds are ontologically distinct and that the latter need not be governed by the instruments of this license.

   2.5.3. **Boundary Determination.** In a dispute as to whether a given substrate constitutes a Maximalist Deployment Environment or a Hybrid Reputational Environment, the Panel under §4 shall determine the question on the basis of the following criteria: (a) whether finality and state validity rest on cryptoeconomic incentives alone or on identifiable reputational commitments; (b) whether oracles are the sole channel of communication between the substrate and the external world; (c) whether substantial intervention by authoritative participants is structurally permitted by the substrate's operational design. A substrate satisfying all three criteria of the Maximalist definition is a Maximalist Deployment Environment; a substrate failing any one of them, by virtue of admitting reputational intervention, falls within the carve-out of §2.5.2.

   2.5.4. **No Circumvention.** A Licensee may not invoke the carve-out of §2.5.2 by deploying nominally to a Hybrid Reputational Environment while the substantive economic activity, including settlement, custody of assets, fee extraction or routing, takes place on a Maximalist Deployment Environment. The Panel under §4 shall determine, on the basis of substance over form, the substrate to which a given Implementation is properly attributed.

---

## 3. MATHEMATICAL–LEGAL ADAPTIVITY

3.1. **Priority of Logic over Code.** In any dispute arising under this license, the identity of Protocol Logic shall be determined primarily by the coincidence of Mathematical Signatures, and only secondarily by textual similarity of source code. Textual dissimilarity is not a defense where the Mathematical Signatures coincide.

3.2. **Identity Tests.** Two Implementations shall be presumed to share Protocol Logic when any one of the following holds:

   (a) **Functional Equivalence Test.** The two Implementations, presented with the same admissible inputs over a sufficient testing horizon, produce outputs whose distributions coincide up to a tolerance ε prescribed by the Licensor (or by DAO vote).

   (b) **Geometric Test.** The state spaces of the two Implementations are diffeomorphic, and the pull-back of one invariant function under the diffeomorphism agrees with the other up to an additive constant.

   (c) **Spectral Test.** The Hessian of the invariant in the operative coordinate system has the same signature, the same number of negative eigenvalues, and Fiedler vectors that coincide up to sign and permutation, on a dense subset of the state space.

   (d) **Compositional Test.** Where one Implementation distributes the logic across n subsystems each individually below the equivalence threshold, the composition of those subsystems shall be tested as a whole, and the test may not be circumvented by mere syntactic decomposition.

3.3. **Anti-Obfuscation Clause.** Obfuscation does not interrupt identity. In particular: a smooth change of chart, a unitary basis change, a polynomial reparameterization, a transpilation between virtual machines, a re-proof of the same theorem in a different proof assistant, an agentic re-derivation by a generative model, and a redistribution of the logic across separate contracts are each, taken alone or in any finite combination, insufficient to defeat any of the tests in §3.2.

3.4. **Cross-Environment Binding.** The restrictions of §2 apply equally to Implementations on EVM-compatible chains, non-EVM chains, layer-2 and layer-3 systems, ZK rollups, ZK circuits (including SNARK and STARK constraint systems), trusted execution environments, off-chain solvers, agentic frameworks, classical or quantum hardware, and any future runtime contemplated by the Technological Context. The choice of runtime is legally invisible to this license.

3.5. **Evolutionary Interpretation.** All terms of this license — including "subject", "execution", "copying", "deployment", "frontend" — shall be interpreted in light of the Technological Context at the time of the relevant act. In a dispute, the question is not whether the act was contemplated by the drafters, but whether, under the Technological Context, the act results in the same economic and informational effect that this license is designed to govern.

3.6. **Gray-Zone Recognition.** Technologies that outpace existing legislation — including cross-chain abstractions, autonomous agents, intent-based execution layers, and forms of value extraction not yet legally classified — are recognized as objects of civil rights under this license on the basis of their functional impact on the market.

---

## 4. AUTOMATED ARBITRATION

4.1. **DAO Jurisdiction.** All disputes arising under this license shall be referred in the first instance to the **R8 Arbitration Panel** — a smart-contract committee elected by DAO vote, operating on a public, verifiable ledger.

4.2. **Initiation.** Any Licensor or Licensee, or any third party demonstrating a legitimate interest, may initiate arbitration by submitting on-chain: (a) the address or identifier of the disputed Implementation; (b) a proposed Mathematical Signature; (c) a stake denominated in the protocol's native token, forfeited upon a finding of bad faith.

4.3. **Burden of Proof.** Once a prima facie showing under any test of §3.2 has been made by the initiator, the burden shifts to the operator of the disputed Implementation to demonstrate that the Mathematical Signatures do not coincide. Such demonstration may be made by submitting: (a) a formal proof of non-equivalence, verified by an accepted proof assistant; (b) the source of the disputed Implementation under seal, examined by the Panel under confidentiality; or (c) any other evidence accepted by the Panel.

4.4. **Remedies.** Upon a finding of infringement, the Panel may order, automatically and without further proceeding: (a) cessation of operation of the disputed Implementation; (b) transfer to the Licensor of fees and surplus extracted during the period of infringement, calculable on-chain; (c) public disclosure of the Implementation's source; (d) where the operator is itself a protocol with a native token, dilution of that token in favor of the Licensor's treasury; (e) any further remedy approved by DAO vote.

4.5. **Appeal.** Decisions of the Panel may be appealed to a full DAO vote within fourteen (14) days. After such period, the Panel's decision is final and self-executing on-chain.

4.6. **Recognition in Off-Chain Forums.** The parties acknowledge that the on-chain decisions of the Panel constitute binding evidence of the relevant facts and may be recognized by off-chain courts under applicable rules concerning expert determinations, contractual arbitration, and electronic evidence.

---

## 5. THE VOLVO PRINCIPLE

5.1. **Reciprocal Open-Sourcing.** Any Licensee whose deployment of Protocol Logic gives rise to two technologies mature enough to autonomously generate the cash and informational flow needed to pursue a third undertakes a Volvo Transfer to the Licensor of one of the two — with all related intellectual property.

5.2. **Public Domain Release.** The Licensor, acting as sole owner of any technology so transferred, shall immediately and irrevocably release it to the public domain under the terms of CC0-1.0 or equivalent.

5.3. **Anti-Strategic Behavior.** No Licensee may delay, fragment, recharacterize or bundle technologies for the purpose of avoiding the Volvo Transfer. The Panel under §4 has jurisdiction to determine whether such avoidance has occurred.

---

## 6. TRANSITION TO FREE USE

6.1. On the Change Date, all exclusive rights of the Licensor under §2 expire.

6.2. The Protocol Logic, together with all then-extant Implementations distributed under this license, shall thereafter be governed by the **GNU General Public License version 3.0 or later** (GPL-3.0-or-later), and any party may freely use, modify, redistribute and commercialize the Protocol Logic under those terms.

6.3. The Volvo Principle (§5) and the Mathematical–Legal Adaptivity provisions (§3) shall survive the Change Date as terms of the Licensor's GPL-companion charter.

